The key insight from Baker and Shostak (1972) is that:
1. To make k an expert requires at least n-1 "informing" calls (where k learns new secrets)
2. To make everyone know k's secret requires at least n-1 "spreading" calls (where k's secret spreads)
3. In a noHo sequence, only calls involving k can serve both purposes simultaneously
4. Calls involving k are counted by v(S,k)

So the total calls needed is at least (n-1) + (n-1) - v(S,k) = 2n - 2 - v(S,k).

